cur before the OOS is ready, causing issues. I’m thinking of using a CountDownLatch to manage this, but I can't access the inner workings directly. Using a client to create the OOS and sending logs repetitively could help, but I want to avoid any missed events. It’s a tricky balance!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing race conditions**\\n\\nI’m looking at how the ObjectInputStream constructor behaves—it returns right after the header is written but before the OOS is added to the list. This creates a tiny race condition, which is tricky. Sleeping isn’t ideal, so I wonder if I could loop the append until a reader gets an event. However, if the initial append occurs before the OOS is added, it complicates things. Using a CountDownLatch from the read thread could help synchronize the process, but the readObject method may block the Future. It's a bit of a juggling act!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_k2fydfcvwUVNU37elxgPHr09|fc_08bfd0ce013e6b170169fbaf7889fc819da6c9229cb568ca0d", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/ch.qos.reload4j/reload4j/1.2.19/build.gradle", "offset": 1, "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 515, "output": 1178, "cacheRead": 13824, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 15517, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778102120176, "responseId": "resp_08bfd0ce013e6b170169fbaf68c93c819d8f0894cbcf011f97"}}
